   * 13. What is your plan for dealing with disappearing students?

The first step is to keep in touch with the students all the time so that they don't disappear. We have a lot of interest in guiding students so that they feel comfortable and excited about our project, and we surely want to see them improving their skills. We'll set short milestones, offering all of our support, so that students can see their progress and see the importance they're achieving within our community.

   * 14. What is your plan for dealing with disappearing mentors?

We have some backup mentors to deal with that event, including the project's release manager, who has a great experience coordinating large groups of people and has extensive knowledge in the GoboLinux internals. He's prepared to assume this position if that shows to be necessary, as well as the others, who'll stay aware of the progress made by the students mentored this summer.

   * 15. What steps will you take to encourage students to interact with your project's community before, during and after the program?

The short milestones, commits and public announcements will certainly help to keep students involved with the project's community all the time. Since there's a good integration between the suggested applications and many other GoboLinux scripts, students will also have a good understanding of all the process and very likely will become a part of our team after the program finishes. And our community is thankfully very integrated and friendly, so that's one more reason for students to stay connected with us later on!

   * 16. What will you do to ensure that your accepted students stick with the project after GSoC concludes?

After seeing their performance, having integrated with the team and leading the development of the tools they developed we'll pretty sure they'll have liked the taste and will keep helping us improve the project as a whole.